    <h1>Speech transitions: words and phrases to connect your ideas</h1>
    <p>June 28, 2018 - Gini Beqiri</p>
  </header>
  <nav class="breadcrumb">
    <!-- Breadcrumb navigation if applicable -->
  </nav>
  <article class="content">
    <section class="introduction">
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>When delivering presentations it’s important for your words and ideas to flow so your audience can understand how everything links together and why it’s all relevant.</p>
      <p>This can be done using speech transitions because these act as signposts to the audience – signalling the relationship between points and ideas. This article explores how to use speech transitions in presentations.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="what-are-transitions">
      <h2>What are speech transitions?</h2>
      <p>Speech transitions are words and phrases that allow you to smoothly move from one point to another so that your speech flows and your presentation is unified.</p>
      <p>This makes it easier for the audience to understand your argument and without transitions the audience may be confused as to how one point relates to another and they may think you’re randomly jumping between points.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="types-of-transitions">
      <h2>Types of transitions</h2>
      <p>Transitions can be one word, a phrase or a full sentence – there are many different types, here are a few:</p>
      <article class="transition-category">
        <h3>Introduction</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>We will be looking at/identifying/investigating the effects of…</li>
          <li>Today I will be discussing…</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="transition-category">
        <h3>Presentation outline</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>There are three key points I’ll be discussing…</li>
          <li>I want to begin by…, and then I’ll move on to…</li>
          <li>We’ll be covering… from two points of view…</li>
          <li>This presentation is divided into four parts…</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <!-- Additional categories as per the original content -->
    </section>
